<DOC><DOCNO> AP880303-0130 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-88 1203EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     03-03 0272</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0278</SECOND><HEAD>16 Killed in Tamil Attack</HEAD><BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tamil rebels disguised as soldiersattacked a village with submachine guns and automatic rifles andkilled 16 people, a military official said today. Most of thevictims were woman and children.   In a separate incident today, three rebels were killed in a gunbattle with police manning a roadblock in the southeast.   Police Chief S. Wijesinghe of the Ampara district said therewere no police casualties. Police seized a Chinese-made T-56 rifleand a submachine gun from the slain rebels, he said.   The military official said the 16 were killed Wednesday atMorawewa village, 27 miles west of Trincomalee port on the easterncoast of Sri Lanka. He spoke on condition of anonymity according toregulations.   The victims included nine children, four women and three men, hesaid. All were Sinhalese except for one Tamil. Three people wereinjured.   The official blamed the attack on members of the LiberationTigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest rebel group. The Tigers havebeen at the forefront of a four-year war for a separate Tamilhomeland and have targeted attacks on the majority Sinhalesecommunity.   The Tigers were blamed for the killings of more than 200Sinhalese in October last year soon after they renounced a peaceaccord aimed at ending the separatist war.   More than 8,000 people have been killed in the Tamil conflictsince 1983. Tamils, who form 18 percent of the country's 16 millionpeople, claim that they are discriminated against by the majoritySinhalese, who form 75 percent of the population.</TEXT></DOC>